{{Infobox book | name = Lessons of the Masters | title_orig = | translator = | image = File:Lessons of the Masters.jpg | caption = | author = [[George Steiner]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United Kingdom | language = English | series = | subject = [[Language]], [[translation]] | publisher = [[Harvard University Press]] | pub_date = 2004 | media_type = Print ([[hardback]]) | pages = | isbn = }}
'''''Lessons of the Masters''''' is a 2004 book by [[George Steiner]]. It is part history, part analysis of the [[mentor]]-[[protégé]] relationship. From [[Socrates]] and [[Jesus]] to [[Husserl]], [[Heidegger]] and [[Arendt]], not leaving out [[Plotinus]], [[Augustine of Hippo|Augustine]], [[Shakespeare]], [[Dante]], [[Christopher Marlowe|Marlowe]], [[Johannes Kepler|Kepler]], [[Wittgenstein]], [[Nadia Boulanger]] and [[Simone Weil]], Steiner shows how much is at stake in the passing on of wisdom and the risks involved.
The book is based on Steiner's [[Charles_Eliot_Norton_Lectures|Norton]] lectures.
